SIMPLE: pilgrim
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pilgrim
<hw>Pil"grim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>pilgrim</ets>, <ets>pelgrim</ets>, <ets>pilegrim</ets>,
<ets>pelegrim</ets>; cf. D. <ets>pelgrim</ets>, OHG.
<ets>piligr⟦imac⟧m</ets>, G. <ets>pilger</ets>, F.
<ets>p⟦egrave⟧lerin</ets>, It. <ets>pellegrino</ets>; all fr. L.
<ets>peregrinus</ets> a foreigner, fr. <ets>pereger</ets> abroad;
<ets>per</ets> through + <ets>ager</ets> land, field. See <er>Per-</er>,
and <er>Acre</er>, and cf. <er>Pelerine</er>, <er>Peregrine</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A wayfarer; a wanderer; a traveler; a
stranger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Strangers and <qex>pilgrims</qex> on the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Heb.
xi. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who travels far, or in strange lands, to visit
some holy place or shrine as a devotee; <as>as, a <ex>pilgrim</ex> to
Loretto; Canterbury <ex>pilgrims</ex></as>. See <er>Palmer</er>.</def>
<rj><au>P. Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pilgrim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pilgrim
<hw>Pil"grim</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a pilgrim, or
pilgrims; making pilgrimages.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With <xex>pilgrim</xex>
steps.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pilgrim fathers</b></col>, <cd>a name popularly given to
the one hundred and two English colonists who landed from the Mayflower
and made the first settlement in New England at Plymouth in 1620. They
were separatists from the Church of England, and most of them had
sojourned in Holland.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pilgrim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pilgrim
<hw>Pil"grim</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To journey; to wander; to
ramble.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Grew. Carlyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pilgrimage</ent>⟦br⟧
